# The template's own machinery is Python (textbooks/research audits, .claude/hooks,
# scripts/preflight + metrics) — its bytecode generates from day one, independent of
# the downstream project's stack. Ignore it unconditionally.
__pycache__/
*.pyc

# --- Add your stack's build artifacts here during onboarding ---
# Examples (uncomment / adapt to your toolchain):
# /target            # Rust
# /build  /dist      # C/C++/CMake, JS bundlers
# node_modules/      # Node
# __pycache__/  *.pyc  .venv/   # Python
# *.o *.obj *.pdb    # native object/debug files

# Profiling / debug captures
*.tracy
*.prof

# Secrets / local env — never commit these
.env
.env.*
!.env.example
*.key
*.pem

# Claude Code local (machine-specific) settings & permission cache — keep the shared .claude/settings.json
.claude/settings.local.json

# OS / editor
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
.idea/
.vscode/*
!.vscode/extensions.json

# Onboarding intake is scratch — keep the README, ignore the dropped docs (optional; delete this block to commit them)
_intake/*
!_intake/README.md

# Note: textbooks/ is intentionally VENDORED — the reference library travels with the project.
# SECTIONS.json is generated (tools/_gen_sections.py) but committed so the agent can grep it without a build step.
